cirrus (abbreviated Ci)

==Noun==

{{Phisics}} [[Meteorology]]. A principal high-level cloud type composed of detached [[cirriform]] elements in the form of white, delicate filaments, of white (or mostly white) patches, or of narrow bands. These clouds have a fibrous aspect and/or a silky sheen. Many of the ice crystal particles of cirrus are sufficiently large to acquire an appreciable speed of fall; therefore, the cloud elements have a considerable vertical extent. [[Wind shear]] and variations in particle size usually cause these fibrous trails to be slanted or irregularly curved. For this reason, cirrus does not usually tend, as do other clouds, to appear horizontal when near the horizon. Because cirrus elements are too narrow, they do not produce a complete circular halo. 

Source: FM 3-6 Field Behavior of NBC Agents.